This paper primarily focuses on user interface design choices and their impact on user decision-making, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of automated techniques for identifying dark patterns, which could fall under the categories of cybersecurity (cs.CR) or information retrieval (cs.IR). The paper also touches on the ethical implications of dark patterns, which could fall under the categories of computer ethics (cs.CY) or social and information networks (cs.SI).
